{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[6]", "headings": "['4.0.2. Higher Dimension Evaluation']"}, "page_content": "4.0.2. Higher Dimension Evaluation\nIt is noteworthy that with an increase in the number of joint combinations, the SRMSE value rises (while R 2 decreases) across all models, as seen in 16k and 7M dimensional joints. This phenomenon occurs because the WGAN models generate a substantially larger number of category combinations compared to the ground-truth population. We analyze this behavior by examining the count of sampling and structural zero data points produced by the models and evaluating the models' performance concerning the category combinations.\n", "type": "Document"}}